VALUES
(42, 17, 7, 42, 14, 5, 5, NULL, 'Service and Responsibility on the Sabbath', 'This connection highlights the theme of duty and care for others, as both passages address the responsibilities of individuals towards their servants and animals. Each verse emphasizes the expectation of action in response to immediate needs, whether in the context of labor or compassion.', 'theme', 0.272, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 17, 8, 42, 12, 37, 37, 'gird thyself, and serve me', 'Servanthood and Readiness', 'This connection highlights the theme of servanthood and readiness in both passages. In Luke 17:8, the servant is instructed to serve the master first, while in Luke 12:37, the master serves the faithful servants, emphasizing the reversal of roles.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 17, 8, 1, 43, 16, 16, 'make ready', 'Dining and Service Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the act of preparing a meal for someone important. In Luke, the servant is instructed to serve the master first, while in Genesis, Joseph commands that a meal be prepared for his guests.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 17, 8, 10, 12, 20, 20, 'serve me, till I have eaten', 'Service and Eating Themes', 'Both passages emphasize the act of serving and eating. In Luke, the servant is instructed to serve before eating, while David eats after worship. This connection highlights the sequence of service and sustenance.', 'theme', 0.3, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 17, 10, 46, 9, 16, 17, 'We are unprofitable servants', 'Servanthood and Duty in Ministry', 'This connection highlights the theme of duty in service. Both passages emphasize the idea of obligation in fulfilling one''s responsibilities, whether as servants or as preachers of the gospel.', 'theme', 0.44699999999999995, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 17, 10, 18, 22, 2, 3, 'unprofitable servants', 'Profitability to God', 'This connection highlights the theme of human unprofitability in relation to God. Both passages emphasize that human righteousness or service does not add value to God, as seen in ''unprofitable servants'' and questioning if man can be ''profitable unto God.''', 'theme', 0.40499999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 17, 10, 60, 5, 5, 6, 'We are unprofitable servants', 'Humility and Servanthood Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of humility in both passages. Luke 17:10 emphasizes the attitude of unprofitable servants, while 1 Peter 5:5-6 calls for humility and submission to one another.', 'theme', 0.40499999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 17, 10, 46, 15, 9, 10, 'We are unprofitable servants', 'Servanthood and Grace Connection', 'Both passages emphasize humility in service and the role of grace. Luke highlights the attitude of unprofitable servants, while Paul acknowledges his labor as a result of God''s grace.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 17, 10, 18, 35, 6, 7, 'We are unprofitable servants', 'Servanthood and Divine Relationship', 'Both passages emphasize the nature of human duty and its limited impact on God. Luke 17:10 reflects on the unprofitability of human service, while Job 35:6-7 questions what humans can truly offer to God, highlighting the insignificance of human righteousness or sin in relation to the divine.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 17, 10, 45, 11, 35, 35, 'We are unprofitable servants', 'Servanthood and Divine Recompense', 'This connection highlights the theme of servanthood and duty in both passages. Luke emphasizes the unprofitable nature of service, while Romans questions who has given to God, implying that true service does not expect recompense.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 17, 10, 20, 16, 2, 3, 'we have done that which was our duty to do', 'Servanthood and Commitment to God', 'This connection highlights the theme of humility in service and the importance of committing one''s actions to the Lord. Both passages emphasize recognizing one''s duty and the need for divine evaluation of one''s intentions.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 17, 11, 42, 9, 51, 52, 'to Jerusalem', 'Journey to Jerusalem', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' journey to Jerusalem, highlighting his determination and the geographical context of Samaria. The mention of Samaria in both verses connects the narrative of his travels.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 17, 11, 43, 4, 3, 4, 'passed through the midst of Samaria', 'Journey Through Samaria', 'Both passages emphasize the journey through Samaria as Jesus travels to Galilee. This connection highlights the significance of Samaria in Jesus'' ministry.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 17, 12, 3, 13, 45, 46, 'stood afar off', 'Connection of Leprosy and Isolation', 'Both passages emphasize the condition of leprosy and the social isolation it brings. In Luke, the lepers stand afar off, reflecting the defilement and separation described in Leviticus.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 17, 12, 42, 5, 12, 12, 'ten men that were lepers', 'Connection of Leprosy Encounters', 'Both passages emphasize encounters with lepers seeking healing from Jesus. The lepers in both instances demonstrate faith in Jesus'' ability to cleanse them from their affliction.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 17, 12, 12, 7, 3, 3, 'lepers', 'Connection of Lepers in Scripture', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of lepers who are marginalized and isolated. The lepers in Luke stand afar off, while the leprous men in 2 Kings discuss their dire situation at the gate, highlighting their shared plight.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 17, 12, 42, 18, 13, 13, 'stood afar off', 'Distance and Humility in Prayer', 'This connection highlights the theme of standing afar off, which signifies a sense of humility and separation from others. Both passages emphasize the characters'' recognition of their unworthiness and their need for mercy.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 17, 12, 14, 26, 20, 21, 'lepers, which stood afar off', 'Connection of Leprosy in Scripture', 'Both passages emphasize the condition of leprosy, illustrating its social and spiritual implications. In Luke, the lepers stand afar off, while in 2 Chronicles, Uzziah is thrust out due to his leprosy, highlighting the separation caused by this disease.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 17, 12, 12, 5, 27, 27, 'lepers, which stood afar off', 'Connection of Leprosy in Scripture', 'Both passages emphasize the condition of leprosy, highlighting its social implications. In Luke, the lepers stand afar off, while in 2 Kings, Naaman''s leprosy is a permanent curse.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 17, 12, 4, 5, 2, 3, 'stood afar off', 'Connection of Leprosy in Scripture', 'Both passages emphasize the exclusion of lepers from the community. In Luke, the lepers stand afar off, reflecting the command in Numbers to put lepers out of the camp.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 17, 13, 40, 9, 27, 27, 'have mercy on us', 'Mercy and Blindness Connection', 'Both passages emphasize a plea for mercy directed to Jesus. The phrase ''have mercy on us'' appears in both contexts, highlighting the desperation of those seeking healing.', 'keyword', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 17, 13, 40, 15, 22, 22, 'have mercy on us', 'Appeal for Mercy', 'Both passages emphasize a plea for mercy directed towards Jesus. In each instance, individuals express their desperation and seek healing, highlighting a common theme of reliance on Jesus'' compassion.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 17, 13, 42, 18, 38, 39, 'have mercy on us', 'Call for Mercy', 'Both passages emphasize a plea for mercy directed to Jesus. In each instance, individuals cry out for help, highlighting their desperation and faith in Jesus'' ability to heal.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 17, 13, 41, 9, 22, 22, 'have mercy on us', 'Appeal for Mercy and Compassion', 'Both passages emphasize a plea for mercy and compassion from Jesus. The phrase ''have mercy on us'' in Luke parallels the request ''have compassion on us'' in Mark, highlighting a common theme of seeking divine help in times of distress.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 17, 13, 42, 5, 5, 5, 'Master', 'Appeal for Mercy and Authority', 'This connection highlights the theme of calling upon Jesus for help. In both passages, individuals address Jesus as ''Master,'' indicating their recognition of His authority and their need for His intervention.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 17, 14, 3, 13, 1, 46, 'Go shew yourselves unto the priests', 'Cleansing and Priestly Authority', 'Both passages emphasize the role of the priest in diagnosing and declaring cleanliness regarding leprosy. In Luke, Jesus instructs the lepers to ''Go shew yourselves unto the priests,'' linking to Leviticus, where the priest''s examination determines one''s status of cleanliness.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 17, 14, 42, 5, 14, 14, 'shew yourselves unto the priests', 'Cleansing and Priest Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the act of showing oneself to the priests as part of the cleansing process. This connection highlights the importance of the priest''s role in confirming healing as prescribed in the Law of Moses.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 17, 14, 12, 5, 14, 14, 'Go shew yourselves unto the priests', 'Healing through Obedience', 'Both passages emphasize the act of following instructions for healing. In Luke, the lepers are cleansed as they go to the priests, while in 2 Kings, Naaman is healed after dipping in the Jordan as instructed.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 17, 14, 40, 3, 15, 15, 'Go shew yourselves unto the priests', 'Fulfillment of Righteousness', 'Both passages emphasize the act of obedience leading to divine cleansing or fulfillment. In Luke, the lepers are cleansed as they follow Jesus'' command, while in Matthew, Jesus speaks of fulfilling righteousness through obedience.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 17, 14, 3, 14, 1, 32, 'Go shew yourselves unto the priests', 'Cleansing of the Leper', 'Both passages emphasize the role of the priest in the cleansing of lepers. In Luke 17:14, Jesus instructs the lepers to show themselves to the priests, aligning with the procedure outlined in Leviticus 14 for their cleansing.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
